data.autoskeleton#<AutoSkeleton>:
The main component. Wraps any subtree and replaces it with a skeleton overlay when loading is true.
import { AutoSkeleton } from "@auto-skeleton/react";
<AutoSkeleton
  id="unique-id"
  loading={boolean}
  className="..."
  options={{ ... }}
>
  {children}
</AutoSkeleton>

data.useautoskeleton#useAutoSkeleton:
Low-level hook for custom integrations. Returns the scan state and a ref to attach to your container.
import { useAutoSkeleton } from "@auto-skeleton/react";
function MyComponent({ loading }: { loading: boolean }) {
  const { ref, bones, isScanning } = useAutoSkeleton({
    id: "my-component",
    loading,
    options: { animation: "pulse" },
  });
  return <div ref={ref}>{/* your content */}</div>;
}

data.quick-start#Quick start:
Wrap any component with <AutoSkeleton> and pass a loading boolean:
import { AutoSkeleton } from "@auto-skeleton/react";
import "@auto-skeleton/react/styles.css";
function UserProfile({ userId }: { userId: string }) {
  const { data, isLoading } = useUser(userId);
  return (
    <AutoSkeleton id="user-profile" loading={isLoading}>
      <div className="profile">
        <img src={data?.avatar} alt="avatar" />
        <h2>{data?.name}</h2>
        <p>{data?.bio}</p>
      </div>
    </AutoSkeleton>
  );
}
When loading is true, the real UI is replaced with a skeleton that mirrors its exact layout. When loading flips back to false, the real content reappears instantly from cache.

